  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key aspects include:\n\n1. Most developed countries have AML laws\n- United States (Bank Secrecy Act)\n- European Union (AML Directives)\n- United Kingdom\n- Canada\n- Australia\n\n2. Common requirements\n- Customer identification\n- Transaction monitoring\n- Reporting suspicious activities\n- Maintaining financial records\n- Implementing compliance programs\n\n3. International standards\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global recommendations\n- Banks and financial institutions must follow these guidelines\n\n4. Penalties for non-compliance\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal charges\n- Loss of business licenses\n\n5. Applies to various industries\n- Banking\n- Real estate\n- Cryptocurrency exchanges\n- Gambling\n- Wealth management\n\nThese regulations aim to prevent financial crimes like money laundering, terrorist financing, and other illegal financial activities.",
